{META_DATA}: CASINO
{META_DATA}: By
{META_DATA}: Nicholas Pileggi
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. RESTAURANT PARKING LOT, LAS VEGAS, 1983 - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: SAM 'ACE' ROTHSTEIN, a tall, lean, immaculately dressed man approaches his car, opens the door, and gets inside to turn on the ignition.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: When you love someone, you've gotta trust them.
{DIALOGUE}: There's no other way.
{DIALOGUE}: You've got to give them the key to everything that's yours.
{DIALOGUE}: Otherwise, what's the point?
{DIALOGUE}: And, for a while... I believed that's the kind of love I had.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Suddenly, the car explodes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Flames, smoke and metal rise into the sky covering the view of the Las Vegas casinos and their signs.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Music in: J.S. Bach - 'St Matthew Passion'.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Ace's body comes flying in - extreme slow motion.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: His body twists and turns through the frame like a soul about to tumble into the flames of damnation.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: MAIN TITLE SEQUENCE.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TANGIERS CASINO FLOOR - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Vignette of ACE through rippling flames, we move in on ACE ROTHSTEIN overseeing the casino.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He lights a cigarette.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Before I ever ran a casino or got myself blown up, Ace Rothstein was a hell of a handicapper, I can tell you that.
{DIALOGUE}: I was so good, that whenever I bet, I could change the odds for every bookmaker in the country.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm serious.
{DIALOGUE}: I had it down so cold that I was given paradise on earth.
{DIALOGUE}: I was given one of the biggest casinos in Las Vegas to run, the Tangiers...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SAN MARINO ITALIAN GROCERY/BACK ROOM, KANSAS CITY - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Vignette of MOB BOSSES sitting at a table surrounded by food and wine like the gods of Olympus.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...by the only kind of guys that can actually get you that kind of money: sixty-two million, seven-hundred thousand dollars.
{DIALOGUE}: I don't know all the details.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Matter of fact...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. BAR, LAS VEGAS - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Vignette of NICKY SANTORO standing at a bar with DOMINICK SANTORO, his brother, and FRANK MARINO, his right-hand man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...nobody knew all the details, but it should'a been perfect.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, he had me, Nicky Santoro, his best friend, watching his ass...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. NIGHTCLUB - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Vignette of GINGER MCKENNA a dazzling thirty-one-year-old blonde seated by a small fiery pool.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...and he had Ginger, the woman he loved, on his arm.
{DIALOGUE}: But in the end...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TANGIERS SPORTSBOOK/ACE'S OFFICE - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ACE looks over the casino he rules.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...we fucked it all up.
{DIALOGUE}: It should'a been so sweet, too.
{DIALOGUE}: But it turned out to be the last time that street guys like us were ever given anything that fuckin' valuable again.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. LAS VEGAS - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Aerial shot coming down out of the clouds over the brightly lit Vegas Strip and off into the blackness of the desert night.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: At that time, Vegas was a place where millions of suckers flew in every year on their own nickel, and left behind about a billion dollars.
{DIALOGUE}: But at night, you couldn't see the desert that surrounds Las Vegas...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. DESERT - DAWN
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Aerial shot swooping along the desert floor, then rising above the mist to reveal mountains in the distance.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: But it's in the desert where lots of the town's problems are solved.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Got a lot of holes in the desert, and a lot of problems are buried in those holes.
{DIALOGUE}: Except you gotta do it right.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, you gotta have the hole already dug before you show up with a package in the trunk.
{DIALOGUE}: Otherwise you're talkin' about a half-hour or forty-five minutes of diggin'.
{DIALOGUE}: And who knows who's gonna be comin' along in that time?
{DIALOGUE}: Before you know it, you gotta dig a few more holes.
{DIALOGUE}: You could be there all fuckin' night.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. LAS VEGAS STRIP, 1973 - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TITLE IN: 'THE STRIP', 'LAS VEGAS', 'TEN YEARS EARLIER'
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ACE is greeted by a casino exec and walked through the brightly lit entrance to the Tangiers Casino.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Who could resist?
{DIALOGUE}: Anywhere else in the country, I was a bookie, a gambler, always lookin' over my shoulder, hassled by cops, day and night.
{DIALOGUE}: But here, I'm 'Mr Sam Rothstein'.
{DIALOGUE}: I'm not only legitimate, but running a casino.
{DIALOGUE}: And that's like selling dreams for cash.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TANGIERS CASINO - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see ACE enter alone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is greeted by BILLY SHERBERT.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They are joined by top executives RICHIE and RONNIE in suits and ties.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: They walk through the casino, past crowded and noisy craps tables, spinning roulette wheels, blackjack tables, poker-faced players at poker tables, and elegant, cordoned-off, black-tie, baccarat tables.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I hired an old casino pal, Billy Sherbert, as my manager and I went to work.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: SHERBERT
{META_DATA}: (Introducing the EXECS to ACE)
{DIALOGUE}: ...And this is Ronnie, who takes care of the card room...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: For guys like me, Las Vegas washes away your sins.
{DIALOGUE}: It's a morality car wash.
{DIALOGUE}: It does for us what Lourdes does for humpbacks and cripples.
{DIALOGUE}: And, along with making us legit...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TANGIERS/HARD COUNT ROOM - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Dolly back from a wall of money.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An employee pours a bucket full of coins into a trough.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera follows progress as numerous coins move on a conveyor system, through a sorting machine.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera reveals several rolls of coins on a lower conveyor as they move up a ladder towards an employee's hands, who then places the rolls on a rack.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...comes cash.
{DIALOGUE}: Tons of it.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, what do you think we're doing out here in the middle of the desert?
{DIALOGUE}: It's all this money.
{DIALOGUE}: This is the end result of all the bright lights and the comped trips, of all the champagne and free hotel suites, and all the broads and all the booze.
{DIALOGUE}: It's all been arranged just for us to get your money.
{DIALOGUE}: That's the truth about Las Vegas.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TANGIERS/FLOOR/SOFT COUNT ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera follows JOHN NANCE carrying a small suitcase and walking through the casino to a door leading to the cashier's cage.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The sign on the door reads 'Authorized Personnel Only'.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He walks through the cage, to another door: 'Notice - Keep Out'.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: We're the only winners.
{DIALOGUE}: The players don't stand a chance.
{DIALOGUE}: And their cash flows from the tables to our boxes ...through the cage and into the most sacred room in the casino ...the place where they add up all the money ...the holy of holies ...the count room.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He opens the door.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see inside the count room from NANCE'S point of view.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: It looks like the area behind a teller's cage in a bank.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A large room, windowless, decor-free.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One side is a mesh cage, opened to reveal stacks of cash boxes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Several COUNTERS in white shirts are gathered around a glass table counting and sorting paper money.)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Now this place was off limits.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUNTER #1
{DIALOGUE}: Verify two thousand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Even I couldn't get inside, but it was my job to keep it filled with cash.
{DIALOGUE}: That's for sure.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: They had so much fuckin' money in there, you could build a house out of stacks of $100 bills.
{DIALOGUE}: And the best part was that upstairs, the board of directors didn't know what the fuck was going on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: At one end of the room the clerks empty the metal boxes and rapidly count the cash at a counting table.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The camera follows a cash 'drop box' being lifted from the stack by a clerk.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He pours the cash on to the table and shows the empty box to a video camera.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: COUNTER #2 rapidly counts the cash and announces:
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUNTER #2
{DIALOGUE}: Five thousand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, to them everything looked on the up and up.
{DIALOGUE}: Right?
{DIALOGUE}: Wrong.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The first counter recounts the cash.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUNTER #1
{DIALOGUE}: Verify five thousand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: The guys inside the counting room...
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stacks of bills lie nearby.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The camera pans across the room to another table manned by a COUNT ROOM EXECUTIVE who repeats the figure and writes it down on a master list.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUNT ROOM EXEC
{DIALOGUE}: Five thousand.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We move back to NANCE opening a cabinet full of stacks of $100 bills.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He opens his suitcase and begins to fill it with cash.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: As he does this, the workers studiously look in other directions.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...were all slipped in there to skim the joint dry.
{DIALOGUE}: They'd do short counts, they'd lose fill slips.
{DIALOGUE}: They'd even take cash right out of the drop boxes.
{DIALOGUE}: And it was up to this guy right here [NANCE], standin' in front of about two million dollars, to skim the cash off the top without anybody gettin' wise ...the IRS or anybody.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: COUNTER #1
{DIALOGUE}: Verify two hundred.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: NANCE closes the case and walks out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: One of the counters dumps another container of money on the table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Now, notice how in the count room nobody ever seems to see anything.
{DIALOGUE}: Somehow, somebody's always lookin' the other way.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, look at these guys [COUNTERS].
{DIALOGUE}: They look busy, right?
{DIALOGUE}: They're countin' money.
{DIALOGUE}: Who wants to bother them?
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, God forbid they should make a mistake and forget to steal.
{DIALOGUE}: Meanwhile, you're in and you're out.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: NANCE exits the count room and proceeds through the lobby of the casino, passing ACE and SHERBERT, to a side exit door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY
{DIALOGUE}: Past the jag-off guard who gets an extra c-note a week just to watch the door.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, it's routine.
{DIALOGUE}: Business as usual: in, out, hello, goodbye.
{DIALOGUE}: And that's all there is to it.
{DIALOGUE}: Just another fat fuck walkin' out of the casino with a suitcase.
{DIALOGUE}: Now, that suitcase was goin' straight to one place: right to Kansas City ...which was as close to Las Vegas as the Midwest bosses could go without gettin' themselves arrested.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: NANCE leaves the casino and gets into a cab parked at the curb.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. KANSAS CITY AIRPORT - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: NANCE arrives.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: He is greeted by ARTIE PISCANO, a gray-haired sixty-year-old underboss.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: TITLE IN: 'KANSAS CITY'
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: That suitcase was all the bosses ever wanted ...and they wanted it every month.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PISCANO
{DIALOGUE}: Hey, John, how are you?
{DIALOGUE}: How was your ride?
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. SAN MARINO ITALIAN GROCERY, KANSAS CITY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: NANCE, with suitcase, and PISCANO leave the car and enter the produce market.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Now this old Mormon fuck here...
{META_DATA}: CUT TO: NANCE, AS HE GETS OUT OF PISCANO'S CAR
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. SAN MARINO ITALIAN GROCERY, KANSAS CITY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: NANCE and PISCANO walk through the grocery store, through the warehouse, past various employees to a doorway leading into the back room, where they are greeted by five older men around a large wooden table with bowls of macaroni and old jelly glasses filled with red wine.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...he had to fly in with suitcases once a month, nice and easy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NANCE
{DIALOGUE}: Somethin' smells good.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PISCANO
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah, they made us somethin' to eat.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: The bosses would come from all over the place: Detroit, Cleveland, Milwaukee.
{DIALOGUE}: All over the Midwest.
{DIALOGUE}: And they would meet in the back of this produce market in Kansas City.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, nobody even knew.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: NANCE shakes hands with AMERICO CAPELLI, sixty-eight, a bald, affable Milwaukee entrepreneur and ARTHUR CAPP, his thirty- year-old yuppie lawyer son.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera continues to pan around the room.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: One of the guys made his mother do all the cooking.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On VINCENT BORELLI, seventy-year-old Kansas City boss.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BORELLI
{DIALOGUE}: Did you ever see that guy Jerry Steriano?
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On VINNIE FORLANO, mid-seventies, an old-timer who once drove for Capone and is now Remo Gaggi's right-hand man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: FORLANO
{DIALOGUE}: Jerry Steriano?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BORELLI
{DIALOGUE}: Yeah.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Now, these old greaseballs might not look it, but believe me, these are the guys who secretly controlled Las Vegas.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PISCANO joins his MOTHER and DAUGHTER by a stove.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PISCANO'S MOTHER
{DIALOGUE}: That man's here again.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Piscano dips a piece of bread into a pot of tomato sauce.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Because they controlled the Teamsters' Union, and that's where you had to go if you wanted to borrow money to buy a casino.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: BORELLI (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: When you've finished with him, I want him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: PISCANO'S MOTHER
{META_DATA}: (Carrying a plate of food to the table where BORELLI and FORLANO are seated.)
{DIALOGUE}: Here you are, gentlemen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: And nobody got a Teamsters' loan, unless the guys in this room knew they were gonna get their little suitcases.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FORLANO gets up from the table and walks toward NANCE.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Guys like this antique here [FORLANO], out of Detroit.
{DIALOGUE}: Or especially guys like Remo Gaggi, the outfit's top boss.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: NANCE embraces REMO GAGGI who's seated on a couch, and sits across from him.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GAGGI
{DIALOGUE}: You got a round figure on it?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Definitely the most important guy in this room.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NANCE
{META_DATA}: (Picking up the suitcase)
{DIALOGUE}: About twenty pounds.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GAGGI
{DIALOGUE}: So?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NANCE
{DIALOGUE}: That's around seven hundred thousand.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GAGGI
{DIALOGUE}: Uh-huh, good.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: NANCE opens the case to reveal the money.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ANDY STONE
{META_DATA}: (Off-screen, from following scene)
{DIALOGUE}: I know it's a little early for Las Vegas...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TANGIERS EXECUTIVE OFFICE PRESS CONFERENCE/BANQUET ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera tilts down a model of the Tangiers Hotel and Casino, then reveals the cover of Business Week magazine with a drawing of PHILIP GREEN, a young corporate type, smiling out under the headline: 'Philip Green, Vegas Wunderkind'.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STONE (O.S.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...but I do want to welcome the ladies and gentlemen of the gaming industry.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: On ANDY STONE, a middle-aged man at a podium giving a speech while GREEN, seated at a table, looks on.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PHOTOGRAPHERS flash their cameras.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ACE and SHERBERT, sitting next to GREEN, also watch the photo op ceremony.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: As far as the world was concerned Andy Stone, the head of the Teamsters' Pension Fund, was a legitimate guy.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STONE
{DIALOGUE}: This is a very auspicious occasion.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: A powerful man.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STONE
{DIALOGUE}: Philip, if you would rise.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Green stands up.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: He even played golf with the President.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STONE
{DIALOGUE}: On behalf of the Teamsters' Pension Fund, it is my pleasure to present to you . . .
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: But Andy also took orders.
{DIALOGUE}: And when he was told to give a pension fund loan to Philip Green...
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STONE
{DIALOGUE}: (Handing GREEN a large cardboard facsimile 'check') ...this check for $62,700,000 for the new Tangiers.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GREEN
{DIALOGUE}: Thank you.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...he did what he was told.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: PHILIP GREEN, who is now the head of the Tangiers Hotel and Casino Corporation, is standing at the podium giving a speech.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Now here was the perfect front man.
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, what the fuck else could he be?
{DIALOGUE}: He didn't know too much.
{DIALOGUE}: He didn't want to know too much, especially that the bosses made the Teamsters lend him the money.
{DIALOGUE}: He wanted to believe the Teamsters gave him all that fuckin' money 'cause he was smart.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: An exploding flash bulb fills the screen.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: GREEN
{DIALOGUE}: ...I say that, knowing full well just how much competition we have in this great city.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: EXT. CHEAP MOTEL OFF HIGHWAY - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see a MAN and a WOMAN swimming underwater.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera reveals that they are in a motel swimming pool with glass portholes.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Expensive cars are parked outside one of the rooms.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Hoods stand around outside the door.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: And where they got Green from - who the fuck knows?
{DIALOGUE}: All I know is that Green was an Arizona real estate hustler, who barely had enough gas money to come and pick up his own fuckin' check...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TANGIERS EXECUTIVE OFFICE PRESS CONFERENCE/BANQUET ROOM - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We return to the press conference.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Photographers snap away.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: In the background are six-foot blow-ups of the Business Week cover.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: The camera moves past GREEN, CAPP and several other men, past SHERBERT, to ACE.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Now, all they needed was somebody they could trust to run the casino.
{DIALOGUE}: And who better than Ace?
{DIALOGUE}: I mean, he was already in Vegas a couple of years and he had the fuckin' place clocked.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: FREEZE FRAME ON ACE.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TANGIERS SWIMMING POOL - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera looks straight down from the top of a hotel to a large pool area.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: But typical Ace...
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TANGIERS SWIMMING POOL/POOLSIDE - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: STONE, in a bathing suit and robe, sits on a lounge chair with a telephone.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ACE, in sports clothes, sits on another chair.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: ...give him a shot at runnin' a casino and he tries to talk you out of it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE
{DIALOGUE}: You know, I don't know if I could do this even if I wanted to.
{DIALOGUE}: The Gaming Commission would never give me a license.
{DIALOGUE}: I have at least two dozen gambling and bookmaking pinches on me.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STONE
{DIALOGUE}: You don't have to have a license to work in a casino.
{DIALOGUE}: All you gotta do is apply for one.
{DIALOGUE}: The state law says you can work in a casino while they're processing your application.
{DIALOGUE}: They got a ten-year backlog.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE
{DIALOGUE}: But what happens when they do find out?
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STONE
{DIALOGUE}: Why would they want to find out?
{DIALOGUE}: We're puttin' a hundred million into this desert here.
{DIALOGUE}: Why would they want to lock us out?
{DIALOGUE}: And besides, they'll never find out.
{DIALOGUE}: All you gotta do is keep changing your job title.
{DIALOGUE}: Like, uh, from Casino Executive to Food and Beverage Chairman.
{DIALOGUE}: And what happens it, they take your application, they put it at the bottom of the pile.
{DIALOGUE}: I know guys workin' there for thirty years, don't have a license.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE
{META_DATA}: (Exhales)
{DIALOGUE}: It's a tough proposition, Andy.
{DIALOGUE}: You, you know, if I did it, I'd have to run it my way.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STONE
{DIALOGUE}: You got it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE
{DIALOGUE}: I'm serious.
{DIALOGUE}: No interference.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: STONE
{DIALOGUE}: Nobody's gonna interfere with your running the casino.
{DIALOGUE}: I guarantee it.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Stone lights a cigarette.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. TANGIERS CRAPS PIT - NIGHT
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ACE blows on a die.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: And that's how that got Ace to take over.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ACES's hands place the die into a micrometer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: They wanted him because Ace ate, slept and breathed gambling.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Camera swish tilts up to ACE, then swish pans to boxman, dealers and players watching him, trying to act calm.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: They worked out a real cute job title too.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: We see the die in the micrometer.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: Tangiers Public Relations Director.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Satisfied the die is not loaded ACE sets it on the craps table, the camera cranes up to reveal the Tangiers Casino floor.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: But the only thing he ever directed was the casino.
{DIALOGUE}: He made his first bet when he was fifteen years old, and he always made money.
{DIALOGUE}: But he didn't bet like you or me.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: A DEALER is sliding chips, tossing them on to a craps table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: You know, havin' some fun with it, shit like that.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE
{META_DATA}: (Approaching the DEALER)
{DIALOGUE}: Where the hell did you learn how to deal?
{META_DATA}: (He reaches down, stacking and arranging the chips.)
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: He bet like a fuckin' brain surgeon.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: ACE
{META_DATA}: (To the chastised DEALER)
{DIALOGUE}: Place the checks properly.
{DIALOGUE}: That's the way you do it.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: DEALER
{DIALOGUE}: Yes, sir.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: He had to know everything, this guy.
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: Direct overhead tracking shot as ACE walks between two rows of gaming tables.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
{DIALOGUE}: He'd find out the kind of inside stuff nobody else knew, and that's what he'd put his money on.
{SCENE_BOUNDARY}: INT. GYM/BOOKIE JOINT, BACK HOME, PRE-SEVENTIES - DAY
{SCENE_DESCRIPTION}: ACE walks past two boxers sparring in a ring, through a doorway into a room where several gamblers are seated around a table.
{CHARACTER_NAME}: NICKY (V.O.)
